l and political change.Swift illuminates many aspects of the story of these popular theaters—the cultural politics and aesthetic ambitions of theater directors and actors, state censorship politics and their role in shaping the theatrical repertoire, and the theater as a vehicle for social and political reform. He looks at roots of the theaters, discusses specific theaters and performances, and explores in particular how popular audiences responded to the plays.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aPopular culturezRussia. 0aTheaterzRussiaxHistory. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Theater / General.2bisacsh  aactors.  aaesthetics.  aaudience response.  acensorship.  aconsumer culture.  adirectors.  adissident.  afactory workers.  aimperial russia.  amoscow.  apeoples theater.  aperformance.  aperforming arts.  apolitical change.  apolitical reform.  apolitics.  apopular culture.  apopular theater.  aprotest.  areform.  aresistance.  arevolution.  arussia.  arussian culture.  arussian history.  arussian politics.  arussian revolution.  arussian theater.  aserfs.  asocial change.  ast petersburg.  atheater critics.  atheater.  atheaters.  atheatrical repertoire.  atsarist russia.  aworking class.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022594740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092587840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520925878423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520925878/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY